nks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the three places called Shelley (Essex, Suffolk, Yorkshire) or from Shelley Plain in Crawley (Sussex). The placenames all derive from Old English <i>scelf</i> ‘rock, ledge, shelf’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Irish (Laois): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Sealbhaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Sealbhach</i>’, a byname from the adjective <i>sealbhach</i> ‘having possessions, wealthy’."],"variants":[{"name":"Shallow","meanings":["Irish (Kilkenny and Wexford): variant of   Shelley  .","English: nickname from Middle English <i>shalou(e)</i> ‘shallow’, conjectured also to mean ‘thin’; perhaps also the same word in the topographic sense of ‘shallow place in a stretch of water’.","Americanized form of French   Chalut  ."]},{"name":"Shelly","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Shelley  ."]},{"name":"Shealy","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Shelley  ."]},{"name":"Sheeley","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Shelley  ."]},{"name":"Sheely","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Shelley  ."]},{"name":"Sheley","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Shelley  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":34,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"John Shelley was born about 1348, in Knockholt, Kent, England as the son of Thomas Shelley. He married Margaret Rolfe about 1371, in Rye, Sussex, E